Monte-Carlo simulations of 1,000 SPRs were run. Simulations were carried out using the Gillespie method (Gillespie, 1976, 1977; Felber et al., 1996). The probability that a molecular species takes a particular reaction pathway is given by the reaction rate for entering that pathway divided by the sum of rates of all available pathways. The dwell time or waiting time before taking one of the pathways is an exponentially distributed random variable with a mean given by the inverse sum of reaction rates for the possible pathways. For example, a free R* molecule's next event could be a binding with either G·GDP, RK, or Arr. To determine which of these happens, we generate a random number, r, uniformly distributed between 0 and 1. G·GDP binds if r < kG
